The paper discusses the dynamic evaluation of graph queries, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several subfields of computer science. The most relevant sub-category is likely cs.DB (databases), as the paper focuses on graph databases and their query languages. The paper also deals with maintaining distances and reachability in graphs, which are topics in cs.DS (data structures) and cs.CG (computational geometry). The use of first-order formulas and regular path queries suggests a connection to cs.LO (logic in computer science), while the application of these techniques to semantic web and biological networks suggests a connection to cs.AI (artificial intelligence).
